    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "thanks. i think i read somewhere that it might be nitrogen specifically. if it is nitrogen, how do i actually test the soil to be sure? and what kind of stuff should i add to change the ph if it's too high?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "To test your soil for nitrogen levels, you can purchase a soil test kit from a gardening store or send a sample to a local extension service for a more detailed analysis. These kits typically involve collecting a small soil sample from different parts of your garden and following the instructions to determine the nitrogen content. If the test confirms a nitrogen deficiency, you can add a nitrogen-rich fertilizer, such as blood meal or fish emulsion, to your soil.\n\nIf your soil pH is too high (alkaline), you can lower it by adding sulfur or aluminum sulfate. These materials help to acidify the soil, making it more suitable for tomato plants. Remember to follow the instructions on the packaging for the correct application rate. It's also a good idea to retest your soil after making adjustments to ensure the pH is now within the optimal range for tomato growth. Keep in mind that soil pH can affect nutrient availability, so maintaining a balanced pH is crucial for your plants' health. Happy gardening!",
      "source": "target",
